    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1975-09-20T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1975-09-20T00:00:00-05:00" n="107"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d107">
                <head>107. Memorandum From the Counselor of the Department of State (<persName
                        corresp="#p_SH_2">Sonnenfeldt</persName>) and <persName corresp="#p_LJM_1"
                        >Jan Lodal</persName> of the National Security Council Staff to Secretary of
                    State <persName corresp="#p_KHA_1">Kissinger</persName>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d107fn1">Source: Ford Library, National
                        Security Adviser, <persName corresp="#p_KHA_1"
                            >Kissinger</persName>–<persName corresp="#p_SBA_1">Scowcroft</persName>
                        West Wing Office Files, Box 21, <gloss target="#t_SALT_1">SALT</gloss>,
                        Chronological File. Top Secret; Sensitive.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1975-09-20">September 20, 1975</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJECT</head>
                    <item>
                        <gloss target="#t_SALT_1">SALT</gloss>: U.S. Position</item>
                </list>
                <p>Attached is a note which you may wish to pass to <persName corresp="#p_GAA_1"
                        >Gromyko</persName> in New York. The note conveys the essence of the
                    position you outlined on September 19 after the conclusion of the first <gloss
                        target="#t_SALT_1">SALT</gloss> session with <persName corresp="#p_GAA_1"
                        >Gromyko</persName>.<note n="2" xml:id="d107fn2">See <ref target="#d106fn2"
                            >footnote 2, Document 106</ref>. The note is printed as <ref
                            target="#d108">Document 108</ref>. <persName corresp="#p_KHA_1"
                            >Kissinger</persName> and <persName corresp="#p_GAA_1"
                            >Gromyko</persName> also met on September 21, 9:30–11:30 p.m., at the
                        Soviet <gloss target="#t_UN_1">UN</gloss> Mission in New York. The
                        memorandum of conversation is <ref target="frus1969-76v16#d196">Document 196
                            in <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1969–1976, Vol. XVI, Soviet
                            Union, August 1974–December 1976</ref>.</note> That position is:</p>
                <p>—2500 kilometer range limit on cruise missiles on heavy bombers, with a ban on
                    development, testing, and deployment above that range.</p>
                <p>—No more than 300 heavy bombers to be equipped with cruise missiles above 600
                    kilometer range.</p>
                <p>—A separate limit of 275 marginally strategic systems for each side:</p>
                <pb facs="0517" n="488" xml:id="pg_488"/>
                <p>—For the <gloss target="#t_US_1">US</gloss>, FB–111s and SLCMs with ranges
                    between 600 and 2000 kilometers</p>
                <p>—For the Soviets, Backfire aircraft.</p>
                <p>—Sea-based cruise missiles above 2000 kilometer range would be banned.</p>
            </div>
